<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="problem-validation">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Use The Mom Test to confirm a problem is real: ask about past behavior, rank evidence on 5-level hierarchy, validate with tier-1/2 signals from non-network respondents.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>problem-validation</tag>
      <tag>customer-discovery</tag>
      <tag>mom-test</tag>
      <tag>customer-interviews</tag>
      <tag>market-research</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Problem Validation</title>

    <summary>A methodology for confirming that a problem is real, painful, and worth solving before writing code. Core rule: use The Mom Test — ask about the user's life and past behavior, never about your idea. Rank evidence on a 5-level hierarchy (payment > commitment > prototype engagement > stated interest > stated problem). Only declare a problem validated when ≥3 tier-1 or tier-2 signals come from non-network respondents.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Most failed products were built for problems that exist but are not urgent or worth paying to solve. Asking "would you use this?" produces compliments, not data. The Mom Test protocol and the evidence hierarchy prevent founders from self-deceiving with flattering but useless feedback. Continuous re-validation catches market drift after launch.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>After idea-generation, before MVP build — confirm the problem is real and painful.</item>
        <item>When growth has stalled and product-problem fit is suspect.</item>
        <item>Before adding a major feature: validate that the underlying job-to-be-done exists.</item>
        <item>During pivots, to test the new problem hypothesis cheaply before writing code.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Post-launch with strong revenue and retention — switch to feature prioritization frameworks.</item>
        <item>High-velocity B2C consumer products where behavior trumps stated preference — run a paid-ads landing-page test instead.</item>
        <item>Regulated or specialized B2B (healthcare, finance) where interviews carry compliance overhead — use expert calls and analyst frameworks.</item>
        <item>When the purpose is validation theatre to feel safe rather than genuine disproof.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="validation-hierarchy">
      <p>The 5-level validation evidence hierarchy, commitment signal types, red flags that indicate weak evidence, and the structured interview opener.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Rank all evidence using the 5-level hierarchy and declare a problem validated only when at least 3 tier-1 or tier-2 signals come from cold, non-network respondents.</statement>
        <rationale>Excitement and verbal interest are cheap. Payment and behavioral commitment are costly signals that indicate genuine motivation. Levels 4-5 are easily faked; agents that weight all five levels equally produce false positives.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>The 5-level evidence hierarchy:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Level 1 (strongest): Users paid for a solution (actual behavior).</item>
        <item>Level 2: Users signed up or made a commitment (letter of intent, pre-order, time investment).</item>
        <item>Level 3: Users engaged deeply with a prototype.</item>
        <item>Level 4: Users expressed strong interest (stated preference).</item>
        <item>Level 5 (weakest): Users said they have the problem.</item>
      </list>

      <p>Commitment signal types:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Time: agreed to a follow-up meeting; used the prototype.</item>
        <item>Reputation: introduced you to their boss or team; referred you to a colleague.</item>
        <item>Money: letter of intent with exec sign-off; pre-order payment.</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>Treat commitment signals as strong only when backed by a concrete past action; "I would definitely introduce you to my team" is level 4, not level 2.</statement>
        <rationale>Letters of intent without executive sign-off are forgeable. Future-tense commitments ("I would") are level-4 interest, not level-2 commitment.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Treat compliments, hypotheticals, and generic statements as red flags that indicate weak or fabricated signal.</statement>
        <rationale>Friends compliment. Hypotheticals ("I would definitely...") are costless to give and carry no predictive value for actual purchase behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Red flag language patterns:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Compliments: "Great idea!", "That's brilliant!", "I love this concept."</item>
        <item>Hypotheticals: "I would definitely use this", "I'd probably pay for that."</item>
        <item>Generics: "Everyone needs this", "Nobody does this well."</item>
        <item>Approval-fishing: answering what they think you want to hear.</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>Open every validation interview with the 5-step Vision-Framing-Weakness-Pedestal-Ask pattern; agents that skip the Weakness step produce performance responses.</statement>
        <rationale>Stating weakness (admitting you might be wrong and want honest feedback) creates psychological safety for the respondent to give critical answers instead of compliments.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>The interview opener framework:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Vision: state the problem you want to solve.</item>
        <item>Framing: explain you have nothing to sell — you are just learning.</item>
        <item>Weakness: humbly acknowledge you might be wrong about the problem.</item>
        <item>Pedestal: emphasize their experience is the expert input you need.</item>
        <item>Ask: request their time and honest experience.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="interview-method">
      <p>Mom Test question rules, bad-question antipatterns, the 3-agent agentic workflow for validation, and best practices for running and scoring interviews.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Ask only about the interviewee's past behavior and current life; never ask about your idea or their hypothetical future behavior.</statement>
        <rationale>Questions about your idea trigger politeness bias. Questions about their past behavior reveal what they actually do, not what they wish they did.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Mom Test question substitutions:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Instead of "Would you use this?" → ask "How do you currently solve X?"</item>
        <item>Instead of "Is this a problem for you?" → ask "Tell me about the last time you dealt with X."</item>
        <item>Instead of "Would you pay $X?" → ask "What have you tried? What did it cost?"</item>
        <item>Instead of "Do you think this is a good idea?" → ask "When was the last time you faced this problem?"</item>
      </list>

      <antipattern>
        <description>LLM-generated interview scripts that re-introduce "would you" / "do you think" question forms.</description>
        <reason>Script-writer agents default to these polite forms because they appear in most interview templates. Lint every agent-generated script before use; reject any question with "would you" or "do you think".</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule>
        <statement>Run at least 5 interviews before making any decision; run at least 10 before claiming confidence. Variance is too high below 5.</statement>
        <rationale>A single enthusiastic interview is anecdote, not signal. Pattern recognition requires minimum sample size; 5 interviews gives themes, 10+ gives confidence.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Recruit cold (outside your network) for at least half of interviews; friends and warm contacts compliment.</statement>
        <rationale>Network contacts give biased feedback. Cold recruits (LinkedIn DMs, Reddit, User Interviews) provide the unvarnished reality that network contacts suppress.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule>
        <statement>Record all interviews (with consent); memory of an interview is reconstructed and self-serving.</statement>
        <rationale>Founders selectively remember the positive signals. Recording enables unbiased re-analysis and is required for agent-based transcript tagging.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>The agentic workflow uses three roles, three agents: (1) Script-prep agent (haiku): converts hypothesis into a Mom-Test-compliant interview guide using the vision/framing/weakness/pedestal/ask pattern. (2) Founder runs the actual interview — LLMs cannot replace this step. (3) Analysis agent (sonnet): ingests transcript, tags red flags (compliments, hypotheticals, generics), extracts commitment signals with severity, scores evidence on the 5-level hierarchy. (4) Decision agent (opus): aggregates at least 5 transcripts, recommends validated/inconclusive/invalidated with rationale and next-step plan. Human approves the final decision.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Never use a synthetic-user simulator as a substitute for real interviews; agent-to-agent "interviews" produce plausible but fabricated data.</statement>
        <rationale>An LLM roleplay of a user produces responses consistent with the prompt framing, not responses consistent with actual user behavior. The resulting "validation" is confirmation bias at scale.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas-and-best-practices">
      <p>Key failure modes and best practices when using AI agents in validation work.</p>

      <p>Failure modes and limitations:</p>
      <list>
        <item>The Mom Test only works if the interviewer is disciplined; agents that auto-generate scripts often slip leading questions back in.</item>
        <item>"Tell me about the last time..." answers are reconstructed memory — recall bias inflates pain frequency.</item>
        <item>Validation hierarchy levels 1-2 (paid / signed up) are strong signal; levels 4-5 (interest / stated problem) are easily faked. Agents weight all five equally if not constrained.</item>
        <item>The "vision → framing → weakness → pedestal → ask" opener feels manipulative when over-rehearsed; people detect the script and respond performatively.</item>
        <item>Commitment signals are forge-able (a "letter of intent" with no exec sign-off is not commitment).</item>
        <item>LLMs cannot conduct interviews — only prepare scripts and analyze transcripts. Replacing the human interview step is the single biggest failure mode.</item>
        <item>Script-writer agents reintroduce "would you" / "do you think this is a good idea?" — lint the output before sending to the founder.</item>
        <item>Tagging agents over-classify hypotheticals as commitment signals when the user is enthusiastic. Require explicit past-tense verb evidence for commitment labels.</item>
        <item>"Strong interest" (level 4) sounds like validation to optimistic founders. The decision agent should weight 4-5 at near-zero unless backed by a behavior trail.</item>
        <item>LLMs auto-summarize transcripts and lose verbatim quotes — keep raw quotes in the log; summaries are insufficient for re-analysis.</item>
        <item>Cross-cultural cues differ — Ukrainian / Eastern-European respondents may give blunter "no"s; LLMs trained on US norms misclassify them as red flags rather than honest signal.</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint: validate/invalidate decision must be human-approved. The agent recommends; the founder decides.</item>
        <item>Avoid agent-only loops: an agent that "interviews" another agent generates plausible but useless data.</item>
      </list>

      <p>Best practices:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Run ≥5 interviews before any decision; ≥10 for confidence. The variance is too high below 5.</item>
        <item>Recruit cold (not your network). Friends compliment.</item>
        <item>Always record (with consent) — memory of an interview is reconstructed and self-serving.</item>
        <item>Score evidence against the hierarchy explicitly — don't let "they were really excited" become the validation. Excitement is hierarchy level 4-5, the weakest.</item>
        <item>Look for behavior trails (what they did before talking to you) over expressed intent.</item>
        <item>Re-validate continuously. The 2025 update is right: validation is not a one-time gate; markets and users drift.</item>
        <item>Disprove, don't prove. The goal is to find out you're wrong cheaply. Confirmation-seeking interviews waste cycles.</item>
        <item>Pair with `pain-point-research`, `jobs-to-be-done`, and `pricing-research` — all four together produce sharper signal than any one alone.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/transcript-tagger.py" purpose="Python script using Anthropic SDK: tags each interview turn as compliment/hypothetical/generic/commitment and returns hierarchy-level score."/>
    </templates>

